This is a calibration cube for verifying your 3D printed dimensions against the dimension of your designs. By knowing your tolerances you can design your work to be a perfect fit when printed. For example, On my makerbot replicator 2 my outside dimensions tend to be 0.3mm bigger. A round hole becomes 0.7mm smaller. Knowing this I can compensate for it in my drawings.  
Included is a PDF with the technical drawing of the part. Print out the drawing, 3D print the cube, measure and compare with the drawing and write down your tolerances on the technical drawing for future reference.  
If you print this, please click the "I made one" on this thingiverse page.
Print how you like. At least 20% infill is recommended.

You will need 2x Nuts, washers and bolts.  Nuts fit inside the switch holder, and screws need to be long enough to go through the MDF and into the nut (approx 30mm), use the holes in the frame for the cable tie to bolt the holder in place (use washers).  
You will also need very small screws (or nut and bolts) to hold the switch in place (approx 2.7mm diameter).  I used small screws.

I want to mount my 3d printer electronics more neatly.  Lots of DIN rail mounts available in thingiverse, but none for DIN Rail.  I don't need an entire length of metal DIN rail, so why not?  
Updated:  Improved the rail profile, and stored it separately.  This profile is a shade smaller and has chamfered corners both for strength and to make it fit better.  The alignment keys on either side are now slightly different sizes to make them fit better.  
I tried to make it customizer compatible, but the DXF import didn't work.  
From other tests, I do recommend printing vertically with a big brim.

These print vertically, and they have alignment tabs so you can make a rail out of many small sections easily.
Download all the files into the same directory. The openscad file has parameters for the length of each section (which has one mounting hole) and the number of sections to stick together. This is a very rudimentary plan - I have access to real din rail mount things at work - I will see how well they mount, or if I need to add cut out a bit of tolerance space, and rounded edges.

comments.text:
The vertical printing works well, but I recommend a wide brim. The alignment notches don't quite fit at the moment on my first print run, and the rails are a bit oversized. I don't know if its a tolerance problem in the model yet, or an issue with my print precision, but I suspect it's a bit of both.
I was able to tightly lock on a commercial DIN RAIL mount device on it, albeit the rail was bending slightly.

description.text: These parts are designed to be used with 1/2 inch Schedule 40 PVC pipe

Created with TinkerCad, these parts use PVC pipe, without the constraints of commercially available plumbing connectors.  
The "sleeve" pieces allow a lot of adjustment, so precisely cut lengths of pipe are usually not required; slide the piece until it fits the connector.  
The holes are set up for 1/4-20 machine screws (1.5 inch) and #6 sheet metal screws (half inch).  
The "end pieces" and "flange pieces" can be printed without supports.   
Test prints are advised as the manufacturing tolerances of PVC pipe are unknown to me.  I used PLA (.35mm nozzle, .2mm layer height, 2 perimeters).  
WARNING; The strength of these pieces has not been determined.  Good layer adhesion is critical. Obviously, prints made with nylon (or other high performance filament) will be much stronger than PLA or ABS. Also, the design of your project is critical; PVC pipe isn't terribly rigid. A connector every 12 inches or so should suffice for most projects but test them first. Print a few connectors, assemble them, and see how much force it takes to break them. That should give you an idea of how suitable these parts are for your project. No warranty is expressed or implied, but have fun.  
UPDATE 13-Apr-2014: There was a layer flaw in the "endpieces" and the file has been replaced with a corrected version.

title: Makergear Prusa auto bed level servo and fan mount's

description.text:
clip on 9g servo and 40mm fan mount for a Makergear Prusa.
I needed a way to mount a 9g servo on my prusa for auto bed leveling and there really aren't any other ways i could figure to do it. I have never needed a fan to cool my stepper motor before but it was easier to design it now than later. It all clips on very securely and the only screws needed were to hold the fan onto the mount. The endstop to servo horn lever printed best scaled up .05 but that could be caused by my abs hopefully you wont need it for these big ugly switches and can just redesign the arm for a much smaller switch.
